<br>
I tent to agree with Leifelf in that many wizards don't use their mana efficiently.  There would be a sliver of health left on the mob we're fighting, and they use their big nuke on it to finish it off.  I also tend to have to tell them (well most nuker classes but wizards being the most obvious cause of their awsome power) to give me a couple rounds before nuking to taunt and stun to gain aggro so the mob doesn't pounce on them.<br>
<br>
Otherwise, when their nukes hit they're an awsome asset to an exp group (more so for a raid).  Evac is required for some places and snaring is essential in pretty much all dungeons. <p>Haka Shakamalakabalsaka <br>
Level 53 Mighty Cavalier <br>
Povar <br>
Hanka <br>
Level 20 Enchanter
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukattootacit.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kattoo Tacit</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/30/01 1:03:31 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Please Read-Your views on Wizards</span><hr size=1> I am 56 and group with a 53 wizard on a regular basis. She can snare and I can stun. I take the hits while she kills, I heal when we are done. Rinse and repeat. If it gets ugly...  its not a problem, we just evac and head back. In a larger group it stays about the same core situation. All we are really doing is adding a Ranger like a DoT, Cleric heals instead of me, Chanter is there so we don't need to worry about the adds, and the left over spot varies. I say 10. Paladins and Wizards go great together IMO.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uriak.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Riak</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/30/01 2:52:14 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Please Read-Your views on Wizards</span><hr size=1>  I grew up with a wizard and two shamans as my core group.  This remains our core group, except we added a good friend warrior and replaced the paladin (me at 52) with an enchanter (me at 40, now 45).  The rest of the group are mid- to late 50's now.  Everybody has played these characters as his or her primary since release except me.  My paladin was my primary for close to 120 days played until my chanter took over.<br>
<br>
Given this experience, I would place our particular wizard as irreplaceable, simply because the group is friends who play well together.  It should be obvious from our classes that this group was not built based on what the class had to offer to a group.  It was built on friendship and good times.  <br>
<br>
As a class, though, I would rate wizards as being just as broken as paladins over 50.  Paladins fair better in the day-to-day experience grind, while wizards offer more in a raid situation.  <br>
<br>
One of the biggest problems both classes face is that neither is considered a core class.  In reality, both classes perform better than the general public perceives, but both are at the bottom of the success scale in Verant's class development.  <br>
<br>
Actual value in a group for a wizard: 5 to 6.  Add breeze, clarity and C2 (or equivalent bard mana buffs) at the appropriate levels and this goes up to about 7.<br>
<br>
A good player can make any class an asset to a group.  The basic toolset available to one playing a wizard (or for that matter, a paladin) is quite simply not as easy to work with as is the toolset that comes with most other classes.  <br>
<br>
Riak<br>
Paladin - 52<br>
Povar<br>
